\begin{Shaded}

\NormalTok{World_Data <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(Date) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\KeywordTok{summarise}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{country=}\StringTok{'World'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{Global_Confirmed_Cases =} \KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(Confirmed_Cases, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm=}\NormalTok{T),}
\DataTypeTok{Global_Deceased =} \KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(Deceased, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm=}\NormalTok{T))}
\NormalTok{World_Data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Death_Rate <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{((World_Data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Global_Deceased}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{World_Data}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Global_Confirmed_Cases) }\OperatorTok{*}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{)}

\hypertarget{collapsing-and-calculating-relevant-variables-in-the-temporary-data.}{%
\section{Collapsing and calculating relevant variables in the temporary
data.}\label{collapsing-and-calculating-relevant-variables-in-the-temporary-data.}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Here, I subset the data so as to properly collapse by country.}
\NormalTok{myvarstemporary <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Date"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Confirmed_Cases"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Deceased"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country[myvarstemporary]}

\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY, Date) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{summarise}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{Total_Cases_Country =} \KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(Confirmed_Cases), }\DataTypeTok{Total_Deceased_Country =} \KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(Deceased))}

\CommentTok{# I next want to calculate the increase in deaths and confirmed cases per day.}

\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{arrange}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY, Date)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{number <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{nrow}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country)}
\NormalTok{First_Day <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{min}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Date)}

\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{New_Confirmed_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{ifelse}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Date }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{First_Day, }\OtherTok{NA}\NormalTok{, Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Cases_Country }\OperatorTok{-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{dplyr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{lag}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Cases_Country, }\DataTypeTok{number=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{))}

\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{New_Total_Deceased_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{ifelse}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Date }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{First_Day, }\OtherTok{NA}\NormalTok{, Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Deceased_Country }\OperatorTok{-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{dplyr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{lag}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Deceased_Country, }\DataTypeTok{number=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{))}

\CommentTok{# There are a few values for which we have negative new deaths and new cases. Intuitively, this shouldn't make sense. This is actually a problem which steps from the COVID data. For example, Iceland has some weird values in the initial dataframe. Although deaths should represent cumulative sums, if we observe the data from 3/15 - 4/05, we note that the number of recorded deaths drops from 5 to 0, then increases back to six as the month progresses. This is a well-documented problem which stems from the original Github data: https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/issues/2379; https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/issues/2165. We can either exclude data points which show a decrease in cumulative deaths (which I haven't done here); or wait for the data to be updated. Because we only drop a few observations from the analysis, I choose to exclude them, and proceed as normal. Note that when we take global sums, this will affect our cumulative totals (as we have excluded observations for certain nations on certain days).}

\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country[}\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{New_Confirmed_Country }\OperatorTok{>=}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{),]}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country[}\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{New_Total_Deceased_Country }\OperatorTok{>=}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{),]}

\CommentTok{# Now, I calculate the total mortality rate per capita, new mortality rate per capita, death rate per capita, and confirmed cases per capita (using data from the United Nations on global demographics for the merge). }

\NormalTok{UN_Population <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read_csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"data/UN_Population_Data.csv"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Location = col_character(),
##   Population = col_double()
## )
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{UN_Population}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{COUNTRY <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{UN_Population}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Location}

\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{25}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Bolivia"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{30}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Brunei"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{43}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Taiwan*"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{46}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Congo (Brazzaville)"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{54}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{"Cote d'Ivoire"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{56}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Congo (Kinshasa)"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{98}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Iran"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{112}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Laos"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{138}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Burma"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{162}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Korea, South"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{163}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Moldova"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{165}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Russia"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{196}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Syria"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{212}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Tanzania"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{213}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "US"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{217}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Venezuela"}
\NormalTok{UN_Population[}\DecValTok{218}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Vietnam"}

\CommentTok{# I subset the file to only include the nations in our final data.}
\NormalTok{UN_Population <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{subset}\NormalTok{(UN_Population, }\KeywordTok{is.element}\NormalTok{(UN_Population}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{COUNTRY, Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{COUNTRY))}

\CommentTok{# Lastly, I join the two dataframes. Note, we lose some observations using inner join (Western Sahara, West Bank and Gaza, MS Zaandam, Kosovo, Diamond Princess, and the Central African Republic.). However, we are not interested in these nations for the purposes of our sample.}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{inner_join}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country, UN_Population)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## Joining, by = "COUNTRY"
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# This allows me to calculate our variable of interest: the mortality rate per capita (for both total deaths, and new deaths).}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Mortality_Rate_Per_Capita =}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Deceased_Country }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Population)}

\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{New_Mortality_Rate_Per_Capita =}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{New_Total_Deceased_Country }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Population)}

\CommentTok{# We might also be interested in cases per capita.}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Cases_Country_Per_Capita =}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Cases_Country }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Population)}

\CommentTok{# Lastly, I want to create a rolling average of the total and new mortality rates per capita, new confirmed cases, and new deaths. This is a bit complicated, so bear with me.}

\CommentTok{# First, I order the data by country and date.}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country[}\KeywordTok{order}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{COUNTRY, Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Date),]}

\CommentTok{# I then construct a seven-day rolling average of confirmed cases, deaths, and both types of mortality rates by country.}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{rolling_average_confirmed =} \KeywordTok{frollmean}\NormalTok{(New_Confirmed_Country, }\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{rolling_average_deceased=} \KeywordTok{frollmean}\NormalTok{(New_Total_Deceased_Country, }\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{total_rolling_average_mortality =} \KeywordTok{frollmean}\NormalTok{(Total_Mortality_Rate_Per_Capita, }\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{new_rolling_average_mortality =} \KeywordTok{frollmean}\NormalTok{(New_Mortality_Rate_Per_Capita, }\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{))}

\CommentTok{# The seven-day rolling average works well, but the algorithm only gives an output after the first week (as we need seven prior values for the sake of our calculation). Ideally, we would want these missing values to have their own rolling averages (i.e. a rolling average of two days for the second date in our dataset; or a rolling average of five days for the fifth date). To do this, I first create a new dataframe with our missing values from the initial seven-day rolling average.}
\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Confirmed <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country[}\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{rolling_average_confirmed)), ]}
\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Total_Deceased_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country[}\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{rolling_average_deceased)), ]}
\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Total_Mortality <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country[}\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{total_rolling_average_mortality)), ]}
\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_New_Mortality <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country[}\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{new_rolling_average_mortality)), ]}

\CommentTok{# Next, I calculate a "new" rolling average for each of our nations, using the roll apply function. The syntax is complicated; but essentially this command allows the user the freedom to vary rolling averages by different "windows" of dates (i.e. three-day average vs. six-day average).}
\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Confirmed <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Confirmed }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{rolling_average_confirmed2 =} \KeywordTok{rollapply}\NormalTok{(New_Confirmed_Country, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{, mean, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =} \OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{fill =} \OtherTok{NA}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{align =} \StringTok{'right'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{partial=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Total_Deceased_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Total_Deceased_Country }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{rolling_average_deceased2 =} \KeywordTok{rollapply}\NormalTok{(New_Total_Deceased_Country, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{, mean, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =} \OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{fill =} \OtherTok{NA}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{align =} \StringTok{'right'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{partial=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Total_Mortality <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_Total_Mortality }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{total_rolling_average_mortality2 =} \KeywordTok{rollapply}\NormalTok{(Total_Mortality_Rate_Per_Capita, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{, mean, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =} \OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{fill =} \OtherTok{NA}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{align =} \StringTok{'right'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{partial=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_New_Mortality <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Missing_Mean_New_Mortality }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{new_rolling_average_mortality2 =} \KeywordTok{rollapply}\NormalTok{(New_Mortality_Rate_Per_Capita, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{, mean, }\DataTypeTok{na.rm =} \OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{fill =} \OtherTok{NA}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{align =} \StringTok{'right'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{partial=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{))}

\CommentTok{# We now want to merge this data back to our temporary file.}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{merge}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country, Missing_Mean_Confirmed, }\DataTypeTok{by =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Date"}\NormalTok{), }\DataTypeTok{all=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{merge}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country, Missing_Mean_Total_Deceased_Country, }\DataTypeTok{by =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Date"}\NormalTok{), }\DataTypeTok{all=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{Temporary_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{merge}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country, Missing_Mean_Total_Mortality, }\DataTypeTok{by =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Date"}\NormalTok{), }\DataTypeTok{all=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\NormalTok{Final_Data_Country <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{merge}\NormalTok{(Temporary_Data_Country, Government_Responses, }\DataTypeTok{by =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Date"}\NormalTok{), }\DataTypeTok{all=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# I now add data on government indicators from: https://info.worldbank.org/governance/wgi/Home/Documents. }

\hypertarget{now-i-calculate-deaths-per-million.}{%
\section{Now, I calculate deaths per
million.}\label{now-i-calculate-deaths-per-million.}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(data.table)}
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(dplyr)}
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(writexl)}
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(readxl)}

\CommentTok{# To calculate deaths per million, news sources divide the number of cumulative (total) deaths by the population size, measured in millions. Luxembourg and Malta have less than a million inhabitants, and thus I do not calculate deaths per million for these nations. Data was pulled from: https://www.statista.com/statistics/1104709/coronavirus-deaths-worldwide-per-million-inhabitants/.}

\NormalTok{Mill_Pop <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read_excel}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"data/Mill_Pop.xlsx"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{Oxford_V1 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{merge}\NormalTok{(Oxford_V1, Mill_Pop, }\DataTypeTok{by =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"COUNTRY"}\NormalTok{), }\DataTypeTok{all=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{Oxford_V1 <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Oxford_V1[}\KeywordTok{order}\NormalTok{(Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{COUNTRY, Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Date),]}

\NormalTok{Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{New_Deaths_Per_Million =}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{New_Total_Deceased_Country }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\StringTok{`}\DataTypeTok{Population (Millions)}\StringTok{`}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{Oxford_V1 <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Oxford_V1[}\KeywordTok{order}\NormalTok{(Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{COUNTRY, Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Date),]}

\NormalTok{Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Deaths_Per_Million =}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Total_Deceased_Country }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Oxford_V1}\OperatorTok{$}\StringTok{`}\DataTypeTok{Population (Millions)}\StringTok{`}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{weekly-growth-rate-visualizations}{%
\section{Weekly Growth Rate
Visualizations}\label{weekly-growth-rate-visualizations}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Here, I filter by first deaths per country.}
\NormalTok{First_Death <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Oxford_V1 }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{dplyr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{dplyr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(Total_Deceased_Country }\OperatorTok{>}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# Now, I calculate the week-by-week growth rate in the rolling average of the mortality rate. This is equivalent to the log[total_total_rolling_average_mortality_(t) – total_total_rolling_average_mortality_(t-7)]. First, I create a variable for weeks by country. This tells us in what week of the year each nation had their first death.}
\NormalTok{First_Death}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{week_num =}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{lubridate}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{week}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{ymd}\NormalTok{(First_Death}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Date))}

\CommentTok{# Next, I generate week-over-week mortality growth rates. Should be (current week - previous week)/previous week. I use two distinct formulas for this calculation.}

\NormalTok{First_Death <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{First_Death }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{dplyr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{dplyr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{total_mortality_growth =} \KeywordTok{log}\NormalTok{((total_rolling_average_mortality}\OperatorTok{/}\KeywordTok{Lag}\NormalTok{(total_rolling_average_mortality,}\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{))))}

\NormalTok{First_Death <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{First_Death }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{dplyr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(COUNTRY) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{dplyr}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(total_mortality_growth_b <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(total_rolling_average_mortality}\OperatorTok{-}\KeywordTok{Lag}\NormalTok{(total_rolling_average_mortality,}\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{))}\OperatorTok{/}\KeywordTok{Lag}\NormalTok{(total_rolling_average_mortality,}\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{))}

\NormalTok{First_Death}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{total_mortality_growth_b  <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{log}\NormalTok{(First_Death}\OperatorTok{$}\StringTok{`}\DataTypeTok{... <- NULL}\StringTok{`}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
